\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q1)
\series default
: Show how the Intermediate Value Theorem follows as a corollary to Theorem
 4.5.2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to\R$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function that maps the connected set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to the real numbers.
 Since every connected subset of the real numbers is an interval, we can
 construct the closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\left[a,b\right]\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 which is a compact and connected set.
 Now we also suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a real number satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(a\right)<L<f\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(a\right)>L>f\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a connected set, the image 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is connected, i.e.
 it is an interval.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(a\right),f\left(b\right)\in f\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in f\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 So there must exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in A$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(c\right)=L$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous, given an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

, such that whenever 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{a-b}<\delta,
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{f\left(a\right)-f\left(b\right)}<\epsilon.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(a\right)<L<f\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(a\right)>L>f\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{L-f\left(a\right)},\abs{L-f\left(b\right)}<\epsilon,
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{a-c},\abs{a-c}<\delta,
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q2)
\series default
: Provide an example of each of the following, or explain why the request
 is impossible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A continuous function defined on an open interval with range equal to a
 closed interval.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Possible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

, then the range is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 which is a closed interval regardless of the domain.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A continuous function defined on a closed interval with range equal to an
 open interval.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Possible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\R\to\R$
\end_inset

 be the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 is both open an closed, the range is equal to an open interval.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A continuous function defined on an open interval with range equal to an
 unbounded closed set different from 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Possible.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\R\to\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A continuous function defined on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 with range equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Not possible.
 A continuous function preserves connectedness.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 is connected, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q$
\end_inset

 is not since it is not an interval, thus a function does not exist.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q3)
\series default
: A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is increasing on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)\leq f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x<y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is increasing on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 and satisfies the intermediate value property, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is increasing on 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 and it satisfies the intermediate value property, then given an 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,c\in B$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)<f\left(c\right)<f\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\in\left(x,y\right).
\]

\end_inset

This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{f\left(x\right)-f\left(c\right)}<\abs{f\left(y\right)-f\left(x\right)},
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{f\left(y\right)-f\left(c\right)}<\abs{f\left(x\right)-f\left(c\right)}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now let's fix 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Given an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, we can construct the interval 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\left\{ x\in B\,:\,\abs{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}<\epsilon\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\min\left(\abs{\sup\left(S\right)-y},\abs{y-\inf\left(S\right)}\right)$
\end_inset

, then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{x-y}<\delta,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{f\left(x\right)-f\left(y\right)}<\epsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Therefore, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(Q4)
\series default
: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be continuous on an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be the set of points where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 fails to be injective; that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\left\{ x\in A\,:\,f\left(x\right)=f\left(y\right)\text{ for some \ensuremath{y\neq x} and \ensuremath{y\in A}}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is either empty or uncountable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is continuous on an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is an injection or if 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs A\leq1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is obviously empty.
 Now we consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is not injective and 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs A>1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs A>1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an uncountable set since it is an interval.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is an injection, there exists at least two points 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x<y$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=g\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We can then form the uncountable closed subset 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left[x,y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(c\right)\neq g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 (if such a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 does not exist, then 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq F$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is uncountable).
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a closed interval and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in continuous, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(B\right)$
\end_inset

 is closed and connected.
 Without loss in generality, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(c\right)>g\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[g\left(x\right),g\left(c\right)\right]=\left[g\left(y\right),g\left(c\right)\right]\subseteq g\left(B\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the intermediate value theorem, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\left[g\left(x\right),g\left(c\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\left(x,c\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\left(c,y\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(z\right)=f\left(k\right)=L$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

